<h1 class="hero-h">How to Use Claude as a Product Manager <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">Less PRD writing. More thinking.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">PM work is dominated by writing — PRDs, specs, release notes, stakeholder updates, customer interview synthesis. Claude can absorb most of that, letting you focus on the parts of PM that AI cannot do: customer discovery, judgment calls, prioritization.</p>
<div class="tldr"><div class="tldr-l">Short answer</div><p class="tldr-p">Top PM Claude workflows: customer interview synthesis, PRD/spec drafting, release notes generation, stakeholder update drafting, competitive analysis, and prioritization frameworks. Setup 5-6 Projects; cuts PM writing time 50-60%; lets PM focus on judgment and customer work.</p></div>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Daily PM workflows</h2><h3 class="h3">1. Customer interview synthesis</h3><p class="body">After each customer interview, paste raw notes or transcript into a Synthesis Project. Get structured outputs: jobs to be done, pain points, current workarounds, language they used, quotes. Build the truth source as you go.</p><h3 class="h3">2. PRD/spec drafting</h3><p class="body">Build a PRD Project with your house template and 5-8 examples of well-shipped specs. Dump in: problem, user, proposed solution, edge cases. Get a structured PRD draft. Heavy edit.</p><h3 class="h3">3. Release notes generation</h3><p class="body">Convert engineering changelogs + product context into customer-facing release notes in 10 minutes vs 90.</p><h3 class="h3">4. Stakeholder update drafting</h3><p class="body">Weekly/monthly product updates to engineering, sales, CS, exec team. Drafted in 15 minutes from a few bullet points.</p><h3 class="h3">5. Competitive analysis</h3><p class="body">Synthesize competitor product launches, pricing changes, marketing positioning into a structured competitive brief.</p><h3 class="h3">6. Prioritization frameworks</h3><p class="body">Pull together effort/impact/confidence scores across the backlog; produce a sequenced roadmap with rationale.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">What to keep human</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Customer interviews.</strong> The conversation is the product. Don't outsource.</li><li><strong>Hard prioritization calls.</strong> AI organizes the inputs; you decide.</li><li><strong>Designer and engineer relationships.</strong> AI does not replace working through hard problems with your team.</li><li><strong>The strategic narrative.</strong> Why this product, why now — your judgment.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">PM-specific traps</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Auto-generated PRDs that engineering ignores.</strong> If engineering doesn't trust the PRD, you wrote it wrong (or didn't edit enough).</li><li><strong>Customer interview synthesis that loses nuance.</strong> Review the AI output against your raw notes; correct misattributions.</li><li><strong>Competitive analysis based only on competitor marketing.</strong> Talk to customers about competitors; do not trust competitor self-positioning.</li><li><strong>Release notes that sound corporate.</strong> Your customers know your voice. Match it.</li></ul></div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">FAQ</h2>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Should I use Claude or a PM-specific AI tool?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Claude usually. PM-specific AI tools tend to be thin wrappers; Claude with your own Projects is more flexible.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Will Claude write good PRDs?</h3><p class="faq-qa">First drafts, yes — if you load examples and provide context. Final PRDs require your judgment about scope, edge cases, and tradeoffs.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Can AI replace customer discovery?</h3><p class="faq-qa">No. AI helps synthesize what you learn. The learning comes from real customer time.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Should engineers see AI-drafted PRDs marked as such?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Probably yes for transparency. Engineering is increasingly AI-fluent; nothing to hide.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">How does PM hiring change with AI?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Lower demand for junior PMs who just write specs; higher demand for PMs with strong customer instincts and judgment.</p></div>
</div></section>

